  "text": "Java's class loading delegation chain in OpenJDK follows a hierarchical parent-first model. The process starts in java.lang.ClassLoader.loadClass(String, boolean) at lines 534-570 in ClassLoader.java, which implements the core delegation pattern: (1) Check if class already loaded via findLoadedClass(name), (2) Delegate to parent class loader if parent != null, or call findBootstrapClassOrNull(name) if parent is null, (3) If not found, invoke findClass(name) to load the class.\n\nThe built-in class loader hierarchy is defined in jdk/internal/loader/BuiltinClassLoader.java (line 89), which extends SecureClassLoader and serves as the base for three built-in loaders. These three loaders are created and initialized in ClassLoaders.java (lines 63-98): (1) BootClassLoader - loads core Java classes from the boot module path (java.base), (2) PlatformClassLoader - loads platform modules, (3) AppClassLoader - loads application classes from the class path. The delegation chain flows: AppClassLoader -> PlatformClassLoader -> BootClassLoader -> Bootstrap (native).\n\nBootLoader.java provides a restricted API to access the boot class loader and manages the unnamed module and native libraries for the bootstrap layer.\n\nAt the HotSpot native level, src/hotspot/share/classfile/classLoader.cpp implements the native class loading mechanisms and includes systemDictionary.hpp (line 40). The SystemDictionary class, defined in systemDictionary.hpp (line 78), acts as the global class cache. It maintains per-ClassLoaderData dictionaries using concurrent hash tables, with the global SystemDictionary_lock protecting additions and concurrent readers ensuring thread-safe access to loaded classes (as documented in systemDictionary.hpp lines 33-64). The SystemDictionary provides core resolution methods like resolve_or_fail() and resolve_or_null() implemented in systemDictionary.cpp, which manage the actual class storage and retrieval across all class loaders.\n\nThis two-layer architecture (Java delegation in ClassLoader and native caching in SystemDictionary) ensures that Java's parent-first delegation semantics are maintained while providing efficient class caching at the native level."
